 which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705185,"age":3,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Foliot I was born about 1103, in England as the son of Foliot FitzRoger von Pitres. He had at least 3 sons and 2 daughters with Agnes de Chesney. He died in 1154, at the age of 52."},"et":{"about 1103–1154":"umbes 1103–1154","1103–1154":"1103–1154","1105–Male":"1105–Surnud","1107–Male":"1107–Surnud","1109–1148":"1109–1148","1100–1148":"1100–1148","1122–1174":"1122–1174","1127–1187":"1127–1187","1129–1203":"1129–1203","1131–Female":"1131–Surnud","1133–Female":"1133–Surnud","1075–Male":"1075–Surnud","1154":"1154","1187":"1187","1131":"1131","1075":"1075","1174":"1174","1129":"1129","1107":"1107","1106":"1106","1127":"1127","1105":"1105","1148":"1148","1203":"1203","1103":"1103","um 1131":"umbes 1131","1122":"1122","1133":"1133","1100":"1100","about 1103":"umbes 1103","um 1133":"umbes 1133","um 1129":"umbes 1129","um 1127":"umbes 1127","1109":"1109","Chipping Warden, Northamptonshire, England":"Chipping Warden, Northamptonshire, England","England":"England"},"fi":{"about 1103–1154":"noin 1103–1154","1103–1154":"1103–1154","1105–Male":"1105–Kuollut","1107–Male":"1107–Kuollut","1109–1148":"1109–1148","1100–1148":